   "source": [
    "### Interpreting Similarity Measures\n",
    "\n",
    "Each metric provides a different mathematical perspective on how \"close\" two vectors (and thus two texts) are:\n",
    "\n",
    "1.  **Cosine Similarity & Dot Product**: These measure the orientation/alignment of vectors. **Higher values** indicate greater similarity (with 1.0 being identical for normalized cosine similarity).\n",
    "2.  **Euclidean Distance**: This measures the straight-line distance between vector points. **Lower values** indicate greater similarity (closer proximity in space).\n",
    "\n",
    "**Confirmation**: As expected, the two science fiction descriptions (SF vs SF) show significantly higher Cosine/Dot values and a lower Euclidean distance compared to the cross-genre pair (SF vs Romance). This confirms that the embedding space successfully clusters semantically related content regardless of the specific metric used."
   ]
