    "### Understanding Reciprocal Rank Fusion (RRF)\n",
    "\n",
    "RRF is a method for combining rankings from different systems. It scores each item based on its rank (R) in a list using the formula: **1 / (k + R)**, where *k* is a constant (default 60) that smooths the impact of high ranks.\n",
    "\n",
    "#### Worked Example\n",
    "If 'Dune' ranks #1 in keyword and #3 in semantic search:\n",
    "- **Keyword Score**: 1 / (60 + 1) ≈ 0.0164\n",
    "- **Semantic Score**: 1 / (60 + 3) ≈ 0.0159\n",
    "- **Total RRF Score**: 0.0164 + 0.0159 = **0.0323**\n",
    "\n",
    "| Query | Keyword Top Result | Semantic Top Result | Hybrid Top Result |\n",
    "| :--- | :--- | :--- | :--- |\n",
    "| 'psychological thriller...' | 'The Silent Patient' | 'Gone Girl' | 'The Silent Patient' |\n",
    "| 'Frank Herbert Dune' | 'Dune' | 'Foundation' | 'Dune' |\n",
    "| 'coming of age...' | 'The Catcher in the Rye' | 'The Perks of Being a Wallflower' | 'The Catcher in the Rye' |\n",
    "| 'award winning SF' | 'Foundation' | 'Starship Troopers' | 'Foundation' |\n",
    "\n",
    "### Why Hybrid Search Wins\n",
    "- **Balanced Precision**: A book ranking moderately in both lists (e.g., #5 in both) may outrank a book that is #1 in only one list, ensuring broad relevance.\n",
    "- **Exact Author Matches**: Keyword search often catches exact author names (like 'Frank Herbert') that semantic models might generalize away.\n",
    "- **Thematic Reach**: Semantic search captures conceptual matches that keyword search misses (e.g., 'survival' matching 'interstellar isolation').\n",
    "\n",
    "### Recommendation\n",
    "For a production book search, we recommend default weights of **semantic_weight=0.6** and **keyword_weight=0.4**. This split rewards the precision of keyword matches (titles/authors) while ensuring that exploratory, natural language queries (the majority of user interaction) are handled with the thematic depth of semantic matching."
   ]
